Although Czech laws provide for the admissibility of a partial abortion procedure (epidural d&c), in practice access is heavily constrained by the absence of compliance with legislation. The shortage of qualified gynecologists, strict enforcement procedures, lack of ultrasound, bureaucratic regulations, unofficial requests by hospital administration to abandon the procedure, and the individual beliefs of doctors prevent many women from receiving this remedy. In practice, the recommended remedial measures are not given to most women. An unsuccessful treatment of an abortion/hyperlabors results in spontaneous abortions or surgical intervention.

The national Human Rights Act obligates Czech parties to have a working and effective system of remedies of human rights violations, including an effective remedy for ethnic discrimination as defined by the Framework Convention. In practice, discrimination complaints have so far been considered on the local/regional level rather than of a national importance, and most of the complaints concerned discrimination in employment. There are no formal means of bringing such complaints before Constitutional Court, although some indirect means appear to be possible. Administrative courts have also adjudicated some cases, but in such instances the courts did not take the allegation of ethnic discrimination seriously, seeing it merely as a means of justifying unjustified refusal to grant employment.
